### Footnotes

<span id="fn_726"></span>[197:4](sbe18071.htm#fr_729.md) See Chap. II, 10.

<span id="fn_727"></span>[197:5](sbe18071.htm#fr_730.md) The same as the
Marhayâ and Marhîyôih of Chap. XXXVII, 82.

<span id="fn_728"></span>[198:1](sbe18071.htm#fr_731.md) This is the second
of the four periods of three thousand years of which time is said to be
composed (see Chap. XXXVII, 11 n). The 'shape of the fire-priest' is one
of the spiritual creations of the first period, in which shape man was
created during the second period, and this primeval man became
Gâyômar*d* (that is, 'a living mortal') through the persecution of the
evil spirit (see § 5) at the commencement of the third period. The first
two steps of this creation are not described to the text of the
Bundahi*s* known to Europeans.

<span id="fn_729"></span>[198:2](sbe18071.htm#fr_732.md) The evil spirit,
who is said to be the origin of falsehood (see Chap. XXXVII, 17).

<span id="fn_730"></span>[198:3](sbe18071.htm#fr_733.md) Which means 'the
living mortal,' or 'the mortal living one.'

<span id="fn_731"></span>[198:4](sbe18071.htm#fr_734.md) The female
archangel Spenda*r*ma*d*, who has special charge of the earth. Or the
phrase may be 'came on to the earth which the beneficent spirit
produced.'

<span id="fn_732"></span>[199:1](sbe18071.htm#fr_735.md) The Mashyâîh and
Mashyâyôîh, or man and woman, of § 2, who are said to have grown up, in
the course of forty years, connected together in the shape of a plant;
but, after a breathing soul had entered them, they became human beings,
and fifty. years later they began to be the progenitors of mankind (see
Bd. XV, 1-30).

<span id="fn_733"></span>[199:2](sbe18071.htm#fr_736.md) Zs. X, 2 states
that eight kinds of metal arose from the various members of the dead
Gâyômar*d*, namely, gold, silver, iron, brass, tin, lead, quicksilver,
and adamant.

